        Selling a Brisbane Property When Owners Disagree 2027: Disputes, Partition and Court Orders
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When co-owners of a property cannot agree on whether to sell, the law does not leave the situation unresolved. Here is how disputes between co-owners work in Queensland and what your options are.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Co-ownership of property works smoothly until it does not. When one co-owner wants to sell and the other does not, you reach a situation where two people have legally equal rights over the same asset and fundamentally different intentions for it. This happens more than most people expect: between friends who bought an investment property together, between siblings who inherited a family home, between former partners after a relationship ends outside the family law system, and between business associates whose arrangements have changed.</p>

      <p>The first thing to understand is that you cannot force a co-owner to sell without going through a legal process. The second thing to understand is that the legal process exists precisely for this situation and it works. The path to resolution is defined, even if it takes time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal position: co-owners cannot be forced to sell unilaterally</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, co-ownership of property is typically held as either tenants in common or joint tenants. In both cases, no individual co-owner has the right to sell the whole property without the consent of the other owners. If you sign a contract to sell a property that you only partially own, you cannot deliver clear title and the contract will fail. The co-owner who refuses to sell cannot be bypassed or overridden by the other party acting alone.</p>

      <p>What you can do is apply to the Supreme Court of Queensland for a partition order under the Property Law Act 1974 (Qld). This is the statutory mechanism for resolving exactly this kind of deadlock. A partition application asks the court to either divide the property between co-owners or order it to be sold, with proceeds distributed according to each owner's entitlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the courts approach partition applications</h2>
      <p>In practice, the vast majority of residential properties cannot be physically divided between co-owners: you cannot cut a house in half and give each party a separate title. The court therefore almost always orders a sale rather than a physical partition. The sale proceeds are then distributed after deducting the costs of the proceedings and the sale.</p>

      <p>Queensland courts will generally grant an order for sale when the co-owners genuinely cannot agree, when the parties have irretrievably broken down in their relationship, or when continued co-ownership is unworkable. The court is not required to find that one party has behaved wrongly. A deadlock between two reasonable people with genuinely different intentions for the property is enough to justify an order. A court may take into account any co-ownership agreement between the parties, any history of one party carrying disproportionate costs, and any special circumstances such as a party's dependence on the property as their primary residence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical steps before going to court</h2>
      <p>Court proceedings are expensive and slow. Before filing a partition application, it is worth working through a structured set of alternatives. The first is a straightforward negotiation: putting a specific proposal to the other co-owner in writing, including a proposed sale price range based on a current market appraisal and a timeline. People who say they do not want to sell often change position when they see a concrete number and a defined process, rather than an open-ended request.</p>

      <p>The second is a buy-out. If one co-owner wants to retain the property and the other wants to exit, the simplest resolution is for the party who wants to keep the property to buy out the other's interest at an agreed price. Engaging an independent valuer to produce a formal valuation gives both parties a defensible figure to negotiate from. A buy-out avoids the transaction costs of a full sale and is often acceptable to both sides when the alternative is litigation.</p>

      <p>The third is mediation. A property solicitor experienced in co-ownership disputes can facilitate a structured mediation that often resolves disputes that parties cannot resolve in direct communication. Mediation is significantly cheaper and faster than litigation and produces agreements that both parties have actively agreed to rather than had imposed on them.</p>

      <p>If none of these approaches produces an outcome, the partition application to the Supreme Court is the backstop. Engaging a property litigation solicitor at that point is not optional: this is specialist legal territory and the procedural requirements are precise.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to the proceeds</h2>
      <p>When the court orders a sale, the property is sold through the open market in the normal way. The gross proceeds are used first to discharge any mortgage over the property, then to pay the costs of the sale and the legal costs of the proceedings as ordered by the court. The remaining balance is distributed to the co-owners in proportion to their ownership shares, subject to any adjustments the court has determined for disproportionate contributions.</p>

      <p>A co-owner who has been paying all of the mortgage, rates, and maintenance costs while the other co-owner has contributed nothing may be entitled to a contribution adjustment that reduces the other party's share of the net proceeds. This is not automatic: it requires evidence and a specific claim, and courts apply discretion in how they treat these adjustments. Again, this is a matter for a solicitor rather than a real estate agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where family law intersects</h2>
      <p>If the co-owners are or were in a de facto relationship or marriage, the property dispute may fall within the jurisdiction of the Family Court rather than the Supreme Court of Queensland. Family law property settlements operate on different principles from general property law, and the Family Court has broad powers to adjust property entitlements in ways that go well beyond a strict proportional division. If there is any domestic relationship dimension to the co-ownership, the applicable legal framework is family law rather than the Property Law Act, and the proceedings would be in a different court. A solicitor experienced in both property law and family law is the right starting point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why early legal advice saves money</h2>
      <p>The most common mistake in co-ownership disputes is waiting too long to engage legal advice. People spend months in circular negotiations that go nowhere, racking up frustration and sometimes paying costs on a property they can neither sell nor manage cooperatively. An initial consultation with a property litigation solicitor takes an hour and costs a fraction of what a contested partition application costs. It also gives you a clear picture of your options and the realistic timeline, which changes how you approach the negotiation entirely.</p>

      <p>A real estate agent's role in a co-ownership dispute is limited but practical: providing an accurate market appraisal that gives both parties a realistic reference point for a buy-out price or a negotiated sale, and then managing the sale itself once the parties have agreed or the court has ordered it. The legal resolution is the work of solicitors. Once that is resolved, the sale process is straightforward.</p>

